The paper focuses on the utilization of robotic assistive devices in everyday life and the detection and processing of erroneous robot actions, which is a key aspect of human-robot collaboration. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves the use of EEG signals for decoding error-related information, which is related to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category. The study also involves the use of two different robots executing the same task, which is related to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The paper also involves the use of deep convolutional neural networks (deep ConvNets), which is related to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of machine learning algorithms for decoding EEG signals, which is related to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
